<blockquote>
<p>Replying to self again to point out that we really don't know shit about human evolutionary history, or anything from prehistory, really. Every time we think we have a handle on it, some archaeologist digs something up that throws a wrench in the whole scheme, leaving us wondering what the actual fuck our past looked like.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Science is about the process of understanding, rather then the actual fundamental knowledge. For example, a singularity in astronomy (black holes), where all our laws and understanding break down, highlights two points. First, it shows the limits of our models. Second, it shows <em>the fact that our models are fundamentally flawed</em>. If our models aren't flawed, then we'd be able to describe the singularity rather than throw our hands in the air and write the mathematical equivalent of &quot;here be dragons.&quot;</p>
<p>Ask any scientist, and they're likely going to agree with the statement, &quot;Humans will never know everything about the universe.&quot; It's all about the journey, not the destination, and often times it's more exciting to discover something that throws everything we thought we knew into a loop. Unless it's your pet theory that got <a href="http://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Jossed">jossed</a>, of course.</p>

