					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/agent-macleod" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1922529); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1922529&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204988" alt="Agent MacLeod" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1922529)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/agent-macleod" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1922529); return false;" >Agent MacLeod</a></span> <span class="odate time_1439252778 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">11 Aug 2015 00:26</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2355421">
									

<p>I'm fine with this definition for science, but archaeology is not what I'd consider science; I'd put it into the category of history and historical studies, which means there should be something at least <em>resembling</em> definitive truth, with minimal room for speculation.</p>
<p>Science allows us to build skyscrapers and spaceships and maybe even warp drives; archaeology tells us how our ancestors built pyramids and monolithic stone temples, and why they bothered with doing so.</p>
<p>So I'm fine with rewriting physics textbooks a couple times a decade, but our failure to have a grasp on things that already happened means that maybe we don't even know what's happening right now, and that's disturbing to me.</p>
<p>I'd also like to point out that everything in this thread fits in the category of &quot;we clearly don't know everything and have to keep digging, both literally and figuratively, to discover the full truth.&quot;</p>

							</div>

								
					
