														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2355438">
									

<blockquote>
<p>I'm fine with this definition for science, but archaeology is not what I'd consider science</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&gt;:( I've got a degree in archaeology.<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-778036-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-778036-1')">1</a></sup><br />
It's classified as a &quot;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_science">social science</a>&quot;. That, in turn, is a subfield of general &quot;science.&quot;</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I'd put it into the category of history and historical studies, which means there should be something at least resembling definitive truth, with minimal room for speculation.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Search &quot;how were the pyramids built&quot; and filter out anything that involves aliens or technology that wouldn't be available to the era (like mechanical engines). Then do the same with Stonehenge. And the Easter Island Moai. And the Nazca Lines.</p>
<p>Long story short, aside from &quot;people did it&quot; and maybe some generalities about the process, nobody really has a freakin' clue. There's been studies where teams actually tested their ideas by making mock-ups using era-accurate tools and techniques to see the viability of what might have happened or how they might have did it, but without a time machine, you're not going to get more than a &quot;you know, this seems like it would be the best way they did it&quot; answer.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>So I'm fine with rewriting physics textbooks a couple times a decade, <strong>but our failure to have a grasp on things that already happened means that maybe we don't even know what's happening right now,</strong> and that's disturbing to me.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Short answer: we don't, in both cases. In, say, ten to twenty years, we'll have a clearer understanding, but right now we don't. People hold pieces of a greater puzzle, but will sometimes refuse to share or lack the knowledge of how important their piece is. Sometimes, peices are lost, forgotten, or even destroyed.</p>
<p>And this is even more true of history; if you go back far enough, <em>ancient writers didn't really bother about things like &quot;accuracy&quot;</em>. Determining what happened from five different texts that gives wildly different accounts of a single battle beyond &quot;so-and-so fought so-and-so and won/lost&quot; told three hundred years after the fact and with the distinct possibility that <em>they're all wrong and <strong>the battle never happened</strong></em> can be a maddening effort. Remember: history is often written by the victors, and they don't like having bad stuff said about them. And sometimes, they'll destroy evidence that goes against what they said.</p>
