					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/scorpion451" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1918720); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1918720&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204988" alt="Scorpion451" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1918720)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/scorpion451" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1918720); return false;" >Scorpion451</a></span> <span class="odate time_1439649884 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">15 Aug 2015 14:44</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2358022">
									

<p>Oddly enough, that's one of the things they actually got right.<br />
A lot of blades, like Conan's blade there, have an unsharpened section at the base called a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ricasso">ricasso</a>. It has several purposes:</p>
<ul>
<li>It lets you shorten the pivot point of a zweihander or a hand-and-a-half sword like that one to make it actually useful in close combat (basically, you grab there and now you've got a stabby short sword with a club on the other end)</li>
<li>It lets you get more torque when you <em>are</em> using it as a slashing sword, because you can get a second hand choked up on the blade and slide it down as you swing, like with a baseball bat. A ginormous, sharp, metal, baseball bat of death.</li>
<li>it lets you block other blades with your blade without damaging your cutting edge. Sometimes they would build swordbreakers into this part</li>
<li>It gives you a thickened portion at the point where your sword is most likely to break</li>
<li>It looks freaking badass, and you can add engravings and pointy bits here for an additional +2 badassery without compromising the blade's funtionality.</li>
</ul>

							</div>

								
